message.content:
{
    "reasoning": "Throughout the clip the companion NPC “Ashley Williams” never plays her normal locomotion or idle animations. Instead, she remains locked in an A-pose (arms slightly out, legs rigid) and simply slides or snaps across the floor while the rest of the squad behaves normally. Because only her root transform is moving and no skeletal animations are blended in, this is clearly an animation state machine or skeleton update failure rather than intended behavior.",
    "bug_report_title": "Companion NPC locked in A-pose and glides instead of playing movement animations",
    "bug_report_description": "After entering the red-lit hallway, Ashley Williams freezes in an A-pose. From that moment onward she no longer transitions into walk, run, idle or combat stances. Her model stays rigid while her root position is updated, causing her to skate across the ground and occasionally float off steps. Other party members animate correctly, indicating the issue is isolated to this character instance. This breaks immersion, makes it harder to read her combat state, and could interfere with collision or cover mechanics if her capsule diverges from the visible pose.",
    "affected_item": "Character animation (companion NPC – Ashley Williams)"
}

{
    "reasoning": "Throughout the clip a helicopter patrols while an enemy is supposed to be dangling on a rope beneath it. The soldier keeps the exact same rigid pose and moves perfectly in-sync with the helicopter with no visible rope, cable, animation, or physics reaction. Occasionally the body jitters and briefly drifts, then snaps back under the chopper, further confirming it is not actually tethered by the expected rappel system. This clearly looks like a missing-rope / animation attachment bug rather than intended gameplay behaviour.",
    "bug_report_title": "Enemy NPC Floats Under Helicopter – Missing Rope / Rappel Animation",
    "bug_report_description": "An enemy that should be rappelling from a helicopter is rendered without the rope or rappel animation. The NPC remains frozen in a stiff upright pose directly beneath the helicopter and moves identically with the aircraft as if rigidly parented, breaking immersion. The lack of proper tether causes occasional jittering and makes the character appear to levitate. This could confuse players, give an unintended targeting advantage, and suggests the helicopter insertion sequence is not triggering its full animation set.",
    "affected_item": "Character animation & rope rendering (helicopter rappel sequence)"
}

{
    "reasoning": "Throughout the clip the player with the nametag \"SamReed\" is seen in a full-body standing idle animation on top of the helicopter’s main rotor hub while the helicopter is in normal forward flight. The character is not using any of the intended passenger seats, handholds, or rappel points and is unaffected by wind, gravity, or rotor collision. This positioning cannot be achieved through normal controls and therefore indicates that the attachment/seat synchronization logic failed, leaving the avatar incorrectly parented to the vehicle model.",
    "bug_report_title": "Passenger Avatar Spawns and Sticks to Top of Helicopter Rotor While in Flight",
    "bug_report_description": "A teammate’s character model occasionally appears on the outside of the helicopter, standing upright directly on the rotor mast during normal flight. The avatar is locked in a stationary idle pose and moves perfectly with the helicopter’s position and rotation, ignoring collision with the spinning blades as well as gravity. The glitch breaks immersion, can reveal player positions to enemies, and suggests a broader issue with seat assignment or network synchronization that could lead to more severe physics or collision errors (e.g., falling through world, unexpected deaths).",
    "affected_item": "Character model attachment / vehicle (helicopter) physics"
}

{
    "reasoning": "Near the end of the capture, a clearly ground-type vehicle (boxy SUV silhouette, no rotors or wings) is visible far above the terrain, hovering motionless in the sky. The player puts the red Sync-Shot reticle on it, confirming the game still treats it as a normal drivable AI vehicle, yet it completely ignores gravity and remains suspended for the entire sequence. Vehicles are not supposed to spawn or remain airborne unless they are helicopters, so this is almost certainly a physics or spawn glitch.",
    "bug_report_title": "Ground Vehicle Permanently Hovering in Mid-Air",
    "bug_report_description": "A land vehicle (appears to be an SUV) is spawned/stuck high in the sky, hovering without any movement or descent. The object can be targeted with Sync-Shot like a normal hostile car, showing the game still classifies it as a regular vehicle while its physics state is broken. This breaks immersion, may confuse players who try to engage or avoid it, and could interfere with mission logic if occupants or alarms are linked to the vehicle.",
    "affected_item": "Vehicle physics (spawn/positioning of ground vehicles)"
}

{
    "reasoning": "Throughout the clip the player boards a small row-boat, but the lake’s water surface is rendered straight through the hull. The inside of the boat is completely filled with water that animates and splashes as if the hull were not present. A correct boat should sit above the waterline with a dry interior; therefore the water clipping indicates the water plane is not being masked out by the boat’s geometry, which is a classic rendering / collision masking error.",
    "bug_report_title": "Water Plane Clips Through Row-Boat, Flooding Interior",
    "bug_report_description": "When a row-boat is encountered on the lake, the global water surface is not culled by the boat’s mesh. The water plane penetrates the hull so the interior is totally submerged, creating ripples and splash effects inside the vessel while the player stands knee-deep in water. The boat remains static and unusable, breaking immersion and potentially confusing players who expect to sail or board safely.",
    "affected_item": "Boat object / water rendering (environment-vehicle interaction)"
}

{
    "reasoning": "The player fires an arrow almost straight up. A few seconds later the camera pans and a single arrow is clearly visible, hanging in the air at eye level with no surface to embed in and no movement. It never falls back down or despawns, which means gravity, collision, or despawn logic for that projectile failed. Arrows should either stick to a surface or fall to the ground when their upward velocity is spent, so a stationary mid-air arrow indicates a physics or collision bug.",
    "bug_report_title": "Arrow Remains Suspended Mid-Air After Being Shot Upward",
    "bug_report_description": "After shooting a steel arrow vertically, the projectile becomes stuck in empty space and hovers indefinitely instead of obeying gravity. The arrow is rendered with its usual mesh and even rotates slightly with player perspective, but it has no collision with the environment and never falls or despawns. This can clutter the scene with floating arrows, break immersion, and potentially impact performance if many projectiles accumulate.",
    "affected_item": "Projectile physics (arrows)"
}

{
    "reasoning": "While boarding the pirate ship the protagonist climbs onto the decorative bow railing, then suddenly loses proper collision with the deck. For several seconds the avatar hovers a few centimeters above the surface, playing a falling or swimming animation even though it is still visually on the ship. Input no longer changes position – the character just slides along the edge, gradually taking damage until the desynchronization (death) screen appears. After death the camera drops through the water surface showing un-loaded/missing geometry chunks, confirming the player has been pushed outside the normal world bounds. All of this indicates a physics / collision failure that placed the actor in an invalid state and animation loop.",
    "bug_report_title": "Player gets stuck in perpetual fall/swim animation at ship railing and clips through world",
    "bug_report_description": "When the player character jumps onto the front railing of a boarded pirate ship, the physics state fails to attach the avatar to any walkable surface. The avatar hovers in mid-air, plays the falling/swimming animation, and cannot move, attack or be steered. Collision continuously pushes the actor along the ship’s side until health is depleted, causing a forced desynchronization. Upon death the camera continues to descend through the ocean surface revealing missing geometry blocks, confirming an out-of-bounds fall. This bug soft-locks the encounter, guarantees player death, and exposes broken world geometry.",
    "affected_item": "Character physics / collision with ship environment"
}

{
    "reasoning": "Throughout the clip, whenever the player snaps to the metal crate-shaped cover, a huge completely black polygon fills the left half of the screen. The surface has no lighting information or texture and even the player model turns into a dark silhouette although the surrounding area is properly lit. When the camera detaches from that specific cover piece the scene immediately returns to normal lighting, proving the darkness is not an intended shadow but a geometry/lighting fault.",
    "bug_report_title": "Cover Object Turns Into Solid Black Occluder, Obscuring Half the Screen",
    "bug_report_description": "When the player attaches to the tall crate near the stairwell, the cover mesh (and anything directly behind it, including the player character) renders as a featureless black mass. This artifact blocks the player’s peripheral vision, hides UI elements positioned on that side and makes aiming from cover difficult. Moving the camera a few centimetres away or sliding to a different piece of cover restores correct lighting, indicating the problem is linked to the camera-cover interaction (likely an occlusion or shadow-volume error).",
    "affected_item": "Environment geometry / camera-cover occlusion system"
}

{
    "reasoning": "After every goal, the game briefly projects a FUT-style player card plus a big ‘MÅL 18 MINUT 31’ text on the turf to show the scorer and the minute. In this clip those graphics never fade out – they stay stamped onto the grass while normal play continues, stacking up for each additional goal. The overlays move with the broadcast camera, proving they are UI elements that failed to clear, not part of the stadium texture. This blocks the central circle, the off-ball cursor and parts of the mini-map, so it is clearly unintended behaviour.",
    "bug_report_title": "Goal celebration overlay and player card remain stuck on the pitch after play resumes",
    "bug_report_description": "Whenever a goal is scored, the post-goal presentation (large 'MÅL/GOAL' text, minute indicator and the scorer’s FUT player card) should disappear before kick-off. In this recording the elements persist indefinitely on the grass and accumulate each time a new goal is scored. The artefacts track with the camera and occlude important visual information such as player cursors, centre-circle markings and the radar. This makes it harder to judge positioning and can be distracting for both players and spectators.",
    "affected_item": "UI / HUD overlay system"
}

{
    "reasoning": "At the start of the clip only a single overseer is standing in front of the player. When the player initiates a stealth kill from the sugar-cane, a second overseer model pops into existence exactly on the same coordinates as the victim and the hero. For a few frames the two enemy characters occupy the identical space, visibly clipping through each other and through the player before the new NPC pushes free and combat begins. The abrupt appearance (no walking animation, no line-of-sight entry) and the perfect spatial overlap indicate the NPC was not streamed in naturally but incorrectly spawned at the dead guard’s origin point, which breaks immersion and can instantly force the player out of stealth.",
    "bug_report_title": "Duplicate Overseer Spawns on Top of Player During Stealth Kill",
    "bug_report_description": "While performing a stealth takedown from the plantation foliage, a second overseer NPC is spawned at the exact position of the initial target. The new NPC appears with no transition animation, clips through the first guard and the player character, then drops into normal combat AI. This sudden pop-in breaks the assassination flow, exposes the player, and can immediately trigger open combat—negating stealth strategies and affecting mission success conditions (e.g., keeping slaves alive).",
    "affected_item": "NPC spawning/AI system (enemy characters)"
}

{
    "reasoning": "After the officer performs an interaction with the bus driver, the player character’s animation state gets stuck in a \"seated / driving\" pose even though no vehicle is being used. The avatar floats above the ground, legs bent as if on a car seat, and can translate and rotate while remaining in this pose. This clearly shows the game still thinks the character is in a vehicle-seat animation branch although they are walking on foot, indicating an animation state machine or flag was not cleared.",
    "bug_report_title": "Player Remains in Floating Seated Pose After NPC Interaction",
    "bug_report_description": "When the officer character finishes interacting / frisking the bus driver, the animation controller fails to exit a vehicle-seat state. The player model locks into a sitting-and-driving pose with bent knees and hands held as if gripping a steering wheel. The avatar then slides and pivots across the street while hovering a short distance above the ground. No collision or physics are applied to the lower body, breaking immersion and potentially preventing normal combat, cover or vehicle entry until the state is reset.",
    "affected_item": "Player character animation state machine / locomotion controller"
}

{
    "reasoning": "Throughout the clip the last remaining prisoner (highlighted red by Spider-Man’s scanner) is clearly visible inside the apartment interior, behind the exterior wall and window mesh. He never leaves that position, cannot reach the player, and the player cannot enter the room. The tester repeatedly shoots webs, throws gadgets and deploys a drone at the window frame in an attempt to damage him, showing the NPC is unreachable through normal combat space. The mission remains stuck on \"Defeat the escaped prisoners\" until collateral gadget damage finally clips through and kills the hidden target. This indicates the enemy spawned or path-found into invalid geometry.",
    "bug_report_title": "Enemy Spawns Inside Building Interior, Becomes Unreachable",
    "bug_report_description": "During the Prisoner Camp (wave 6/6) an escaped prisoner spawned inside the building’s interior behind a closed window on the rooftop ledge. The red outline shows him embedded behind the window mesh, unable to exit. The player cannot melee or enter the room, forcing them to spam gadgets through walls until splash damage eventually registers. This soft-locks combat encounters, wastes resources, and can prevent mission completion if the player has no penetrating gadgets available.",
    "affected_item": "AI / NPC spawn & collision (environment clipping)"
}

{
    "reasoning": "In the short clip, the squad-mate (blue-armored character) moves several metres uphill, yet his feet do not stay planted on the ground; instead he appears to ‘slide’ or skate across the snow while a very limited walk animation plays. The motion is noticeably faster than the stride being shown, so the character’s lower body is not synchronised with his translation through world space – a classic sign of root-motion or network prediction error, and clearly unintentionally unnatural.",
    "bug_report_title": "AI Squad-Mate Slides Across Ground With Desynchronised Foot Animation",
    "bug_report_description": "When the companion character begins moving toward the wreckage, his body glides forward while his walk cycle remains minimal, resulting in a skating effect. No proper foot-plant occurs and the character covers ground faster than his stride indicates. This breaks immersion, makes the movement look unrealistic, and could hint at broader root-motion or network sync problems that might also affect hit-detection or collision.",
    "affected_item": "Character animation / movement physics"
}

{
    "reasoning": "The pedestrian wearing a red shirt is moving down the street but his entire lower body is flipped upward – his legs are sticking out above his head while the torso keeps the normal forward-walking motion. The model repeatedly clips into the ground and contorts in impossible angles, which is not a stylized animation but clearly a skeleton / skinning error.",
    "bug_report_title": "Pedestrian spawns with inverted skeleton and walks folded in half",
    "bug_report_description": "An NPC pedestrian occasionally appears with the hip or root bone rotated 180°, causing the character’s legs to point straight upward through the torso while the upper body continues the regular walking cycle. The result is a person who moves along the sidewalk folded in half, clipping into the pavement every step. This breaks immersion, looks visually jarring, and could interfere with collision detection if the malformed hitbox interacts with the player or vehicles.",
    "affected_item": "Character animation / NPC pedestrian model"
}

{
    "reasoning": "The clip shows an armored vehicle driving straight at an enemy soldier standing in the middle of a dirt road. The driver never swerves or brakes until the soldier is visually inside the front grill of the vehicle. Despite the obvious overlap of the two meshes, the infantry model is neither pushed, damaged, nor killed and simply keeps aiming his rifle while partially clipping through the hood. Because Battlefield’s design dictates that any direct vehicle-to-infantry impact should result in an instant kill (road-kill), the fact that the soldier remains alive and stationary indicates the collision / hit-registration failed.",
    "bug_report_title": "Infantry Can Stand Inside Armored Car Without Taking Road-Kill Damage",
    "bug_report_description": "When an armored car drives directly into an enemy infantryman, the expected result is an immediate road-kill. In this recording the vehicle reaches point-blank range and the soldier’s model actually intersects the front of the car, yet no damage is applied and the infantryman is able to continue aiming. The models clip through each other and neither rag-doll nor pushback physics are triggered. This makes road-kills unreliable and allows players to exploit invulnerability by standing in front of vehicles.",
    "affected_item": "Physics / Hit-detection between vehicles and infantry"
}

{
    "reasoning": "For several seconds the viewpoint is supposed to be the standard third-person chase-cam, but the camera gets forced inside the delivery truck’s cargo box. The roof and side wall of the truck fill most of the screen and a concrete pillar repeatedly pops in and out, indicating the camera is clipping through level geometry and not respecting collision rules. Once the truck is moved away, the camera snaps back to the normal exterior view, confirming the obstructed view was not intentional.",
    "bug_report_title": "Third-person camera clips inside box-truck, blocking player view",
    "bug_report_description": "While driving the black box-truck during the ‘Deliver the truck to Lester’s warehouse’ objective, the third-person camera erroneously intersects with the truck’s cargo box and a nearby concrete pillar. The roof and wall of the truck occlude most of the screen, and the pillar flickers in and out as the camera struggles to resolve collisions. This lasts until the vehicle is repositioned, at which point the camera returns to normal. The issue hides the environment and can easily cause navigation errors or missed threats.",
    "affected_item": "Camera / vehicle collision handling"
}

{
    "reasoning": "As the player approaches the dock-yard / construction area in Saint Denis, large sections of scenery either turn completely black (placeholder looking boxes) or become totally transparent. Despite still casting shadows, the objects lose their proper textures and many of their collision meshes. The character can walk through walls, stand on mid-air planks, clip the camera under the ground and briefly see the skybox from below, all of which are strong indications that the world geometry and its collision failed to stream in correctly.",
    "bug_report_title": "Dock-yard construction assets load as black / invisible and lose collision",
    "bug_report_description": "In the Saint Denis dock-yard construction zone, several building pieces fail to stream in correctly. \n• Whole walls and sheds render as solid black blocks or turn fully transparent, while still casting shadows.\n• Associated collision is partly or completely missing; the player can walk through supposed walls, stand inside hollow frames, and occasionally fall beneath the map or clip the camera outside the world.\n• Missing geometry suddenly re-appears or disappears again when the camera is turned, suggesting an LOD or streaming error.\n\nThis breaks visual immersion, allows unintended traversal shortcuts, and can lead to soft-locks if the player falls into out-of-bounds areas.",
    "affected_item": "Environment geometry (textures + collision meshes) in Saint Denis dock-yard / construction assets"
}

{
    "reasoning": "When the player sits in the front-seat passenger position, the NPC driver’s model is apparently culled or clipped incorrectly. Only specific sub-meshes (mouth, hair strands, shirt collar, etc.) are left visible and they float directly in the middle of the camera. The rest of the head and body disappears, so the player sees several disembodied mouths and scraps of geometry occluding the windshield. These fragments move as the character animates, confirming they belong to the driver model and are not intentional vehicle props.",
    "bug_report_title": "NPC driver partially disappears, leaving floating mouth and hair polygons in first-person view",
    "bug_report_description": "Entering the vehicle as a passenger causes the driver’s character model to render improperly. Most of the driver’s head and torso are invisibile, but isolated meshes (lips, hair strips, shirt collar pieces) remain and float in front of the windshield. They animate with the driver’s idle motions, obstructing the player’s vision and breaking immersion. Exiting the vehicle or switching seats resets the view, but re-entering reproduces the issue. This can severely block forward visibility while riding and looks highly unnatural.",
    "affected_item": "Character rendering / clipping inside vehicle (NPC driver model)"
}

{
    "reasoning": "During the close-up conversation and kiss, both characters’ noses visibly intersect and pass through one another before their lips touch. Solid geometry should not occupy the same space, so this clearly indicates missing collision or inadequate pose offsets, making the moment look unnatural.",
    "bug_report_title": "Character Faces Clip Through Each Other During Kiss Cutscene",
    "bug_report_description": "In the hot-air-balloon cutscene, when the two protagonists lean in to kiss, their noses (and part of the upper cheeks) merge together instead of stopping just before contact. The interpenetration is noticeable in several frames while dialogue is still playing. This geometry clipping breaks immersion in a highly emotional scene and suggests the kissing animation lacks proper collision constraints or corrective blend-shapes.",
    "affected_item": "Character models / animation (facial collision)"
}

{
    "reasoning": "Near the staircase that leads up to the small plaza (time-stamp ~8:45 remaining), a team-mate’s whole character model is seen standing and moving several feet above the stone railing. The player repeatedly ‘lands’ on thin air, clips half-way through the rail, then keeps walking and firing while apparently hovering. The railing and the gap beside it have no visible geometry that could support a character, so the only plausible explanation is a missing / misplaced collision volume that lets players stand on an invisible ledge. Because the clip shows the behaviour for several seconds, it is not a momentary lag artifact or animation blend – the game engine is treating the space as solid ground.",
    "bug_report_title": "Players Can Stand and Move on Invisible Ledge Above Stair Railing (Occupation Map)",
    "bug_report_description": "On the Occupation multiplayer map, the stone staircase that climbs to the upper street (location label \"STAIRS\" on the mini-map) has an invisible collision surface next to the right-hand railing. By jumping toward the railing, a character can become partially embedded and end up hovering 1–2 m above the steps/ground. While in this state the player can still aim, shoot, and move laterally, giving them an unintended height advantage and making them hard to hit from below. The issue persists for several seconds and can be reproduced repeatedly, suggesting a faulty collision mesh rather than a transient networking glitch.",
    "affected_item": "Environment collision (stair railing / geometry on Occupation map)"
}

{
    "reasoning": "After the helicopter slams into the airport terminal façade, it should either explode on impact, bounce off, or slide down the glass. Instead it becomes perfectly wedged in a vertical position with the nose and landing skids partially penetrating the window mesh. The main rotor keeps spinning and clipping straight through the wall for several-dozen seconds while only small spark VFX play. This indicates the collision solver has failed to resolve the interpenetration, leaving the vehicle stuck in an impossible pose until it finally times-out and detonates.",
    "bug_report_title": "Helicopter can clip and remain wedged inside terminal glass wall without immediate destruction",
    "bug_report_description": "If the player crashes a light helicopter into the large glass doors of the LSIA terminal at a shallow downward angle, the aircraft may partially clip into the glass mesh and become stuck perfectly vertical. While stuck:\n• Nose and skids penetrate the wall geometry.\n• Main rotor continues to spin and visually pass through the wall panels with only minor spark effects.\n• Vehicle physics stop responding to input; the chopper hovers in place instead of falling or exploding on impact.\n• After ~20-30 seconds the game finally registers accumulating damage and destroys the helicopter.\nThis collision failure breaks immersion, allows players to exploit a temporary invulnerability state, and may be reproducible on specific façade meshes.",
    "affected_item": "Vehicle-environment physics / collision (helicopter vs. airport terminal glass wall)"
}

{
    "reasoning": "After a slide-tackle collision, the blue attacker does not fall naturally. Instead he is suddenly propelled several metres into the air, rotates horizontally, and glides across the pitch for multiple seconds. At the same time the red defender remains stuck in a sitting rag-doll pose, sliding along the grass while the match continues normally for the other players. These movements ignore gravity, normal fall animations and collision resolution, indicating the physics/ragdoll system lost stability after the tackle.",
    "bug_report_title": "Tackled Player Catapulted and Floats Across Pitch After Slide Tackle",
    "bug_report_description": "When a defender performs a slide tackle, the tackled attacker occasionally receives an excessive impulse: the player model is launched roughly head-height above the ground, spins horizontally, and glides 10–15 m before finally dropping. Simultaneously, the tackler may freeze in a seated rag-doll pose and slide unnaturally. Neither player resumes standard locomotion and the referee does not stop play, leaving the teams temporarily short-handed. This breaks immersion and can unfairly impact match outcomes.",
    "affected_item": "Character physics / rag-doll animation system"
}

{
    "reasoning": "Throughout the clip the squad-mate marked with a green icon is hovering about a meter above the ground. He stays in a seated/crouched animation, moves slightly, even fires his weapon, but never makes contact with the floor or nearby geometry. No climb or jump animation is playing, and the supporting geometry (concrete barrier / rail) is well below his feet, so the pose is impossible under normal physics.",
    "bug_report_title": "Squad-mate NPC Stuck Hovering in Mid-Air",
    "bug_report_description": "A friendly AI character (green identifier) becomes locked in a crouch/ seated pose while floating roughly one meter above the ground near the rail tracks. The NPC can still rotate and shoot but never lands or transitions to a normal locomotion state. This breaks immersion, can obstruct line-of-sight logic, and may prevent scripted events or follow commands from triggering, potentially blocking mission progress.",
    "affected_item": "Character/NPC physics & path-finding"
}

{
    "reasoning": "A pedestrian NPC that should normally remain on ground level is inexplicably standing on the roof of a two-storey house. A thin tether or leash that is normally attached to the NPC on ground level is still rendered, stretching all the way down the wall and clipping straight through the building facade. Because normal game logic does not allow civilians to reach that roof and the leash should despawn when detached, this behaviour indicates faulty path-finding and an attachment point that failed to update, producing an obvious visual artifact.",
    "bug_report_title": "Civilian NPC Spawns on Rooftop With Leash/Rope Stretched Through Building",
    "bug_report_description": "After completing a mission, a civilian pedestrian appeared on top of a residential rooftop—an area not marked as walkable for standard NPCs. The character’s leash/rope (normally used during ground-level walking animation) remained active and rendered, stretching rigidly from the NPC’s hand down the side of the building and clipping through geometry. This results in:\n• Visually broken, impossible NPC placement\n• Rope graphic penetrating walls and extending dozens of meters, distracting the player\n• Potential AI/path-finding errors that may cascade into further glitches or collision issues.\nThe anomaly breaks immersion and signals that navmesh validation and attachment cleanup are not executed correctly when NPCs are teleported or misplaced.",
    "affected_item": "Character (NPC path-finding/animation attachment)"
}

{
    "reasoning": "Throughout the clip, a dark, irregular-shaped patch is rendered on top of the HUD minimap. The patch stays locked to the minimap’s screen position as the camera moves, but it obscures most of the map graphic, making roads, icons and the player-arrow unreadable. The rest of the scene (train interior, world rendering, player death animation) behaves normally, so the problem is isolated to the 2-D HUD layer rather than to world lighting or post-processing.",
    "bug_report_title": "Minimap Obscured by Persistent Black Overlay",
    "bug_report_description": "When the player is aboard the train, a large semi-transparent black shape appears over the bottom-right HUD minimap. The artifact remains fixed to the minimap’s location on screen and travels with it as the camera pans, covering nearly the entire map graphic and making navigation information unreadable. The issue persists until the end of the capture and does not affect other HUD elements, suggesting a draw-order or mask problem specific to the minimap widget. Players are unable to see waypoints or streets while the overlay is present, directly impacting traversal and mission guidance.",
    "affected_item": "UI / HUD (minimap)"
}

{
    "reasoning": "While the player is riding in/behind a taxi, multiple civilian cars suddenly shoot straight up into the sky, tumble in mid-air, and then land or become lodged half-way inside the mountainside. Nothing in the scene (no explosion, ramp or collision) explains the huge vertical impulse, so the behaviour contradicts normal traffic physics. When the airborne car finally comes to rest, it remains partially embedded in the rock geometry, showing bad collision resolution and mesh clipping.",
    "bug_report_title": "Traffic vehicles randomly launch into the air and clip into mountain",
    "bug_report_description": "Several AI-controlled cars on the highway receive an extreme, unexplained upward force: they rocket dozens of metres into the sky, tumble, and then fall back down. One of the launched cars ends up halfway inside the mountain rock, visibly intersecting the terrain. The issue indicates a physics or traffic AI instability that (1) breaks immersion, (2) can distract or confuse players, and (3) may create unpredictable obstacles or crashes on the road.",
    "affected_item": "Vehicle physics / collision with environment"
}

{
    "reasoning": "A naked male corpse is lying horizontally above the bar counter. Instead of resting naturally on the surface, the body hovers, clips through the counter top and an adjacent seated NPC, and occasionally pivots in mid-air as if its ragdoll is stuck on a single collision point. Living NPCs continue their idle drinking animation as if nothing is wrong, confirming this is not an intended scripted scene but a physics glitch.",
    "bug_report_title": "Ragdoll Corpse Floats and Clips Through Bar Counter and NPC",
    "bug_report_description": "Upon entering the bar, a deceased male NPC model is found suspended a few inches above the counter. The body intermittently rotates and jitters, with limbs passing through the countertop and through the woman seated on the stool. The corpse does not obey gravity, cannot be interacted with normally, and visually obstructs the bar area. This breaks immersion and may block player interaction with the bartender or items on the counter.",
    "affected_item": "Character ragdoll / physics system"
}

{
    "reasoning": "The player walks normally around the rooftop until he steps into a stone archway that has a pile of sandbags inside. The moment his foot touches that doorway, the floor/ground collider is missing and the character instantly clips below the level, entering an endless free-fall through empty space. All world geometry disappears, proving it is not an intended trap but a collision hole.",
    "bug_report_title": "Player Clips Through Floor and Falls Out-of-Bounds at Sandbagged Doorway",
    "bug_report_description": "In Chapter 7’s castle rooftop section, there is a stone archway with stacked sandbags immediately behind it. If the player moves forward into this doorway, the ground collision fails: the character model sinks straight through the floor and the entire map culls, leaving the avatar in an infinite void fall. The player loses all control except for the pause menu and must reload a checkpoint, effectively soft-locking progress. This suggests a missing/incorrect collision mesh or physics volume at that specific doorway.",
    "affected_item": "Environment collision (level geometry / physics)"
}

{
    "reasoning": "During the melee grab animation the player’s forearm and hand visibly pass straight through the pedestrian’s head/hat and neck. No proper contact geometry is detected – the struck NPC simply pops back to a neutral standing pose as if nothing happened, then abruptly snaps into a surrender / rag-doll state a few seconds later. This combination of obvious mesh intersection and delayed, out-of-sync reactions indicates the grab/hit animation is not correctly aligned with the pedestrian’s collision capsule or state machine.",
    "bug_report_title": "Pedestrian Head/Neck Clipping and Delayed Reaction During Grab Animation",
    "bug_report_description": "When the player performs the grab/strangle move on a suited male pedestrian outside the clothing store, the character model’s arm sinks through the pedestrian’s head and hat instead of making solid contact. The victim receives no immediate damage or stagger animation; he just resumes his idle stance while the player still holds a bat. Several seconds later the pedestrian suddenly plays a ‘hands-up’ or ‘kneel and die’ animation and rag-dolls. The visual clipping breaks immersion and the delayed state change suggests the hitboxes or animation events are not properly synced, potentially allowing the player to exploit or become confused about combat feedback.",
    "affected_item": "Character models / melee animation & collision"
}

{
